arch:property.oc:show_val: This is a layer of destruction debris that covered the north half of the trench. It was excavated when the trench was re-opened, following the bulldozer reconstruction of the columns. This locus was almost certainly not deposited at one time (see above, Locus 3). However, it was sufficiently homogenous to be removed as one, particularly as much of the removal was done using the bulldozer. This was done in order that the entire area might be cleared before the end of the season; the nature of the area was already known from the excavation of Trench 23 in 1995. Locus 9 is notable chiefly for the numerous architectural fragments that were found. Of these, the vast majority are carved limestone capital fragments of acanthus leaves. One particularly important fragment is the acanthus covered corner of the capital from a pier, probably that of one of the Anta walls (Pierre). It has been placed on top of the East Anta. The north of the locus, above the Stylobate, had been disturbed. In this area were found many architectural fragments that had already been labeled with green paint by the German team. These were measured and re-numbered according to our record keeping system. The pottery from this locus was heterogeneous. Two pieces of marble wall-tiling and one of marble floor-tiling were found. There was also much plaster recovered from this area. This included 34 pieces of red painted plaster, probably from the East Pronaos column, as there is red plaster remaining on the West Pronaos column. There were also 222 pieces of molded, unpainted plaster. This was found primarily near the bases of the East Porch (Pia and Nadine) columns and probably once covered them. A coin, which is almost certainly Nabataean, was found as well.
Phase XII: Use levels, robbing and abandonments continue.

Major collapse evidenced by a heavy layer of destruction debris containing soil, ashlars occurring over an extended time period based on the presence of a layer of charcoal in the southeast of the trench.

Phase IX: Major CE 363 earthquake leads to the collapse of major temple architectural elements including the West Porch columns. Collapse and accumulation of debris around the temple east columns and on top of the lower risers of interior and rear staircases. Buckling of the west intercolumnar wall. Possible conflagration. Primary fluvial layer is deposited.
Phase XI: Further collapse post CE 5th c., possibly the result of the earthquake of CE 512. The east Porch columns and Central Arch collapse and fluvial deposits continue to accumulate.

Phase X: Site abandonment post major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c, Upper level robbing occurs including the upper treads of East and West Interior and Rear Staircases, and the associated upper landings. Evidence of squatter camps in the South Corridor and Central Arch.
Phase XIII: Major collapses continue into the Islamic period.
